At the moment JIRA uses lower case to generate index without codes while the RDBMS abstraction layer adds quotes to the definitions enforcing that index are all in lowercase. This can result into errors such as :

{noformat}
ORA-20000: Unable to analyze INDEX "JIRA"."INDEX_AO_60DB71_SUB730851836"
{noformat}

This can be avoided by either:

# Creating JIRA index in uppercases
# Prevent the RDMS from adding quotes to the index statement.

The first option will be more feasible and easy to control. This is an example of a sample script from JIRA
{noformat}
DROP TABLE AO_60DB71_STATSFIELD;
CREATE TABLE AO_60DB71_STATSFIELD ( ID NUMBER(20) NOT NULL, RAPID_VIEW_ID NUMBER(20) NOT NULL, TYPE_ID VARCHAR2(255) NOT NULL, PRIMARY KEY (ID) );
CREATE INDEX index_ao_60db71_sta1907922871 ON AO_60DB71_STATSFIELD (RAPID_VIEW_ID);
ALTER TABLE AO_60DB71_STATSFIELD ADD CONSTRAINT fk_ao_60db71_statsf2144119068 FOREIGN KEY (RAPID_VIEW_ID) REFERENCES AO_60DB71_RAPIDVIEW (ID);
{noformat}

